00:29:32.580 --> 00:29:33.880
I promise.

00:29:33.880 --> 00:29:35.180
Yeah?

00:29:35.180 --> 00:29:37.400
&gt;&gt; Hi. So one of the things
that I enjoyed the most

00:29:37.400 --> 00:29:39.740
about the entire
trilogy was the way

00:29:39.740 --> 00:29:43.490
that you were layering
history and science and all

00:29:43.490 --> 00:29:44.790
of these things on
top of each other.

00:29:44.790 --> 00:29:47.900
And so I was actually wondering
if you could talk a little bit

00:29:47.900 --> 00:29:49.200
about the difficulty

00:29:49.200 --> 00:29:52.930
of world-building
over actual history?

00:29:52.930 --> 00:29:54.230
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Yeah.

00:29:54.230 --> 00:29:55.530
Great question.

00:29:55.530 --> 00:29:58.030
So as a historian, as you
can imagine, I have a kind

00:29:58.030 --> 00:30:00.670
of fairly allergic
reaction to history going

00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:05.190
out the window, be
it in anything.

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:07.810
And so the way I
felt about it was --

00:30:07.810 --> 00:30:10.260
and it may be a little
different for other people

00:30:10.260 --> 00:30:11.970
who write historical fiction.

00:30:11.970 --> 00:30:17.560
I felt like if something was
knowable to me as a historian,

00:30:17.560 --> 00:30:20.490
that's what it needed
to be in the book.

00:30:20.490 --> 00:30:23.370
But if something was unknowable,

00:30:23.370 --> 00:30:27.140
like what was Kit Marlowe
[phonetic] doing on Halloween

00:30:27.140 --> 00:30:30.860
in 1590, I could invent it.

00:30:30.860 --> 00:30:34.130
So I'll give you an example
of how that played out.

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:38.480
Matthew Roydon, who was a
real person and was part

00:30:38.480 --> 00:30:41.140
of my research for
my master's thesis,

00:30:41.140 --> 00:30:44.330
which was on George
Chapman's Shadow of Night.

00:30:44.330 --> 00:30:46.710
Any of that sound familiar?

00:30:46.710 --> 00:30:50.100
He was this annoying, hanging
chad of my master's thesis

00:30:50.100 --> 00:30:54.650
who the Shadow of Night was
dedicated to him, but he was,

00:30:54.650 --> 00:30:58.080
like, the Forrest Gump
of the 16th century.

00:30:58.080 --> 00:31:01.910
But I couldn't find any real
concrete information about him.

00:31:01.910 --> 00:31:03.260
So I thought, well,
he's perfect,

00:31:03.260 --> 00:31:05.320
that's exactly what a
vampire would be like.

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:07.030
I'm going to use Matthew Roydon.

00:31:07.030 --> 00:31:10.710
So actually even in Discovery
of Witches, you were falling

00:31:10.710 --> 00:31:13.480
in love with a 16th-century
dead poet.

00:31:13.480 --> 00:31:16.620
Because I use whatever I
knew about Matthew Roydon

00:31:16.620 --> 00:31:18.430
to shape Matthew
Clermont's character.

00:31:18.430 --> 00:31:21.460
Because he was this sort
of fixed, historical thing.

00:31:21.460 --> 00:31:25.670
Then as I started writing it, I
thought, well, Shadow of Night,

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:28.390
they're there in October,
they'll be out by Christmas.

00:31:28.390 --> 00:31:31.770
And as I kept writing, as
I do, in my loop de loops,

00:31:31.770 --> 00:31:36.790
and we got closer and closer
into spring, I thought, oh, no.

00:31:36.790 --> 00:31:39.380
Because one of the other things
I knew about Matthew Roydon was

00:31:39.380 --> 00:31:42.940
that he was in Prague
in March and April.

00:31:42.940 --> 00:31:45.100
I had no intention
of going to Prague.

00:31:45.100 --> 00:31:48.160
We were going to go to
London and come back.

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:51.240
But as the plot unfolded, I
said, I'm sorry, the book --

00:31:51.240 --> 00:31:53.000
you know, it's going
to take me longer.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:54.300
I have to go to Prague.

00:31:54.300 --> 00:31:55.630
[ Laughter ]

00:31:55.630 --> 00:31:58.420
And people said, what do you
mean you have to go to Prague?

00:31:58.420 --> 00:32:00.090
And I said, Matthew
Roydon went to Prague.

00:32:00.090 --> 00:32:01.390
It's now March.

00:32:01.390 --> 00:32:02.690
I have to go to Prague.

00:32:02.690 --> 00:32:04.510
And they said, no one
knows that but you.

00:32:04.510 --> 00:32:07.260
[ Laughter ]

00:32:07.260 --> 00:32:11.090
And I said, I know, but I know
it, and I can't un-know it.

00:32:11.090 --> 00:32:14.220
And so that's sort of my
relationship with history.

00:32:14.220 --> 00:32:16.530
So people keep saying to
me, well, why is Marcus --

00:32:16.530 --> 00:32:18.340
when they read the drafts
of Time's Convert --

00:32:18.340 --> 00:32:21.460
why is Marcus in that
battle and not this battle?

00:32:21.460 --> 00:32:24.460
Because that's what was
happening and I'm not going

00:32:24.460 --> 00:32:25.940
to sort of rearrange history.

00:32:25.940 --> 00:32:30.010
So I almost think of it
as like a pinball machine.

00:32:30.010 --> 00:32:31.660
You know how when you
used to shoot the ball

00:32:31.660 --> 00:32:33.920
of the pinball machine, there
were these little flippers

00:32:33.920 --> 00:32:36.170
that kept the -- that's how I
think of history in my books

00:32:36.170 --> 00:32:39.020
as little flippers that
are just keeping the ball

00:32:39.020 --> 00:32:41.080
within a set of boundaries.

00:32:41.080 --> 00:32:45.440
And it's sometimes challenging
to work really closely

00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:49.530
in that parameter, but
it's a challenge I enjoy,

00:32:49.530 --> 00:32:51.910
how to stretch the truth
without breaking it.

00:32:51.910 --> 00:32:53.210
A little bit like magic.

00:32:53.210 --> 00:32:54.510
Thanks for your question.

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:56.470
[ Laughter ]

00:32:56.470 --> 00:32:57.770
&gt;&gt; A similar question.

00:32:57.770 --> 00:33:00.500
Being that you are a researcher

00:33:00.500 --> 00:33:06.100
and an academic before
you were a novelist,

00:33:06.100 --> 00:33:08.290
at what point do you
stop yourself following

00:33:08.290 --> 00:33:11.580
down the rabbit hole of
delicious search in order

00:33:11.580 --> 00:33:15.710
to write the actual
words of the novel?

00:33:15.710 --> 00:33:18.580
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: OK, so
this is a great question.

00:33:18.580 --> 00:33:21.550
I don't stop myself from
falling down a rabbit hole.

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:27.250
If you want to know why there
was a gap between Shadow

00:33:27.250 --> 00:33:29.060
of Night and the Book of Life,
it's because I kept falling

00:33:29.060 --> 00:33:32.040
down rabbit holes,
scientific rabbit holes,

00:33:32.040 --> 00:33:34.790
and not being able
to extricate myself.

00:33:34.790 --> 00:33:37.960
So, you know, I spent 2
and a half weeks in Shadow

00:33:37.960 --> 00:33:41.360
of Night trying to figure
out how long the voyage

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:44.630
from Woodstock to Europe
would take in November.

00:33:44.630 --> 00:33:48.290
I called long distance
eventers who work on horses

00:33:48.290 --> 00:33:52.030
over long distances and had
long, complicated discussions

00:33:52.030 --> 00:33:55.240
about the speed you --
how long you can canter,

00:33:55.240 --> 00:33:59.410
how long you can gallop, when
you have to change horses.

00:33:59.410 --> 00:34:02.060
It ended up being one
sentence in Shadow of Night.

00:34:02.060 --> 00:34:04.100
[ Laughter ]

00:34:04.100 --> 00:34:06.680
Two weeks of unending research.

00:34:06.680 --> 00:34:08.640
It was the most frustrating
two weeks.

00:34:08.640 --> 00:34:09.940
They don't teach you this

00:34:09.940 --> 00:34:11.720
in graduate school,
just so you know.

00:34:11.720 --> 00:34:16.600
And so it is one of the
delights of writing a book.

00:34:16.600 --> 00:34:19.600
And even though it feels
like a weird rabbit hole,

00:34:19.600 --> 00:34:22.470
it almost always
produces something useful.

00:34:22.470 --> 00:34:25.900
So now that I have a little
bit more confidence in myself

00:34:25.900 --> 00:34:31.160
as a writer, I panic less when
I fall down those rabbit holes.

00:34:31.160 --> 00:34:34.780
But it's always a -- where
it's a balancing act is

00:34:34.780 --> 00:34:36.080
in the writing.

00:34:36.080 --> 00:34:37.380
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:34:37.380 --> 00:34:39.740
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Because
historical information is

00:34:39.740 --> 00:34:42.450
like jalapeno pepper
or cilantro:

00:34:42.450 --> 00:34:44.820
a little goes a long way.

00:34:44.820 --> 00:34:47.300
So you don't want to sort of
take everything you've learned

00:34:47.300 --> 00:34:49.550
about history -- and I know you
have read books like this --

00:34:49.550 --> 00:34:53.510
and dump them in so that
it overwhelms the story.

00:34:53.510 --> 00:34:56.550
It should be a spice,
a flavoring, an accent.

00:34:56.550 --> 00:34:58.880
So one of the things that
I do is I ask myself,

00:34:58.880 --> 00:35:01.540
if this story was
set in the present,

00:35:01.540 --> 00:35:07.020
would I spend three
pages describing a table?

00:35:07.020 --> 00:35:08.870
No, right?

00:35:08.870 --> 00:35:12.500
So if I'm in the past, I try to
hold that same standard to it.

00:35:12.500 --> 00:35:18.030
That if in fact Diana sits down
at a table in the 16th century,

00:35:18.030 --> 00:35:20.590
I don't devote -- I
could devote three pages

00:35:20.590 --> 00:35:23.080
to describing the
table, but I try not to.

00:35:23.080 --> 00:35:24.680
And that's how I sort
of balance it out.

00:35:24.680 --> 00:35:25.980
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:35:25.980 --> 00:35:27.280
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Great.

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:28.580
Yeah?

00:35:28.580 --> 00:35:29.880
&gt;&gt; Hi. Well, USC
grad, so fight on.

00:35:29.880 --> 00:35:31.180
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Fight on.

00:35:31.180 --> 00:35:33.310
&gt;&gt; I hope that Philippe
