00:36:02.540 --> 00:36:05.010
Give it up to Eleanor Oliphant.

00:36:05.010 --> 00:36:06.310
I love that book.

00:36:06.310 --> 00:36:07.610
&gt;&gt; Did that.

00:36:07.610 --> 00:36:08.910
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Did that.

00:36:08.910 --> 00:36:10.210
[ Laughter ]

00:36:10.210 --> 00:36:11.510
I also have to say I just
finished reading Girl,

00:36:11.510 --> 00:36:14.520
Wash Your Face, by Rachel
Hollis, which I had a lot

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:15.960
of fun with, and which I felt

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:18.670
at times she was
writing directly to me.

00:36:18.670 --> 00:36:22.910
I tend to be a professional
nonfiction reader,

00:36:22.910 --> 00:36:27.430
so I'm actually reading
a book about papermaking,

00:36:27.430 --> 00:36:29.700
because why not as a
historian of the book,

00:36:29.700 --> 00:36:32.430
and I'm enjoying that.

00:36:32.430 --> 00:36:36.320
So yeah, those are three off the
top of my head that are right

00:36:36.320 --> 00:36:39.540
on my to read pile or
have just read pile.

00:36:39.540 --> 00:36:40.840
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:36:40.840 --> 00:36:42.140
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness:
Yeah, you're welcome.

00:36:42.140 --> 00:36:43.440
Hi.

00:36:43.440 --> 00:36:45.740
&gt;&gt; Hi. I run an apothecary
museum here

00:36:45.740 --> 00:36:47.590
in Alexandria right
outside of D.C.

00:36:47.590 --> 00:36:59.030
that you should totally come
and visit, 18th, 19th century.

00:36:59.030 --> 00:37:02.470
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: OK,
that sounds like fun.

00:37:02.470 --> 00:37:07.560
&gt;&gt; There's people
who've been there, also.

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:09.970
And an apothecary, that's
my particular interest.

00:37:09.970 --> 00:37:18.120
I'm curious what sources you
used for some of the botany

00:37:18.120 --> 00:37:22.190
that you talk about
in the witchcraft

00:37:22.190 --> 00:37:24.120
that are in the books.

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:25.420
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Yeah.

00:37:25.420 --> 00:37:26.720
It's a great question.

00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:28.020
So I spend, like I
said, lots and lots

00:37:28.020 --> 00:37:32.970
of times reading scientific
and medical notebooks.

00:37:32.970 --> 00:37:36.570
So I spend lots of
times with notebooks

00:37:36.570 --> 00:37:39.720
that medical practitioners
kept of their medical receipts,

00:37:39.720 --> 00:37:41.470
their cures, their recipes.

00:37:41.470 --> 00:37:43.870
Similarly, I work
on a lot of people

00:37:43.870 --> 00:37:47.460
who would have self-identified
as magicians

00:37:47.460 --> 00:37:50.190
in the 16th century, and
those include their spells

00:37:50.190 --> 00:37:52.680
and their plant lore.

00:37:52.680 --> 00:37:55.970
So the Bodleian Library
probably has one

00:37:55.970 --> 00:37:57.270
of the biggest collections

00:37:57.270 --> 00:38:04.280
and the British Library has
the second biggest collection

00:38:04.280 --> 00:38:08.060
for what I do, which
is 16th century.

00:38:08.060 --> 00:38:14.320
But I did just buy an early
19th-century medical formulary

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:15.620
on eBay.

00:38:15.620 --> 00:38:16.920
&gt;&gt; There's a lot out there.

00:38:16.920 --> 00:38:19.210
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: I know,
there's amazing stuff on eBay.

00:38:19.210 --> 00:38:28.560
So I'm sort of delving
into the wonderful world

00:38:28.560 --> 00:38:34.700
of 19th century drugs
right now and medicines.

00:38:34.700 --> 00:38:36.350
&gt;&gt; Come see me.

00:38:36.350 --> 00:38:39.180
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Well,
it's amazing, because again,

00:38:39.180 --> 00:38:42.610
this book is, like,
breaking apart.

00:38:42.610 --> 00:38:48.470
There's newspaper clippings in
