00:39:25.440 --> 00:39:26.740
&gt;&gt; First of all, thank you.

00:39:26.740 --> 00:39:28.040
You've made the last couple
years completely enjoyable late

00:39:28.040 --> 00:39:29.340
at night.

00:39:29.340 --> 00:39:30.640
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Oh, thanks.

00:39:30.640 --> 00:39:31.940
&gt;&gt; And during the day and
in the middle of the night.

00:39:31.940 --> 00:39:33.240
How has all this
changed your life?

00:39:33.240 --> 00:39:34.540
How has it impacted you?

00:39:34.540 --> 00:39:35.840
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: I
have a bigger classroom,

00:39:35.840 --> 00:39:37.140
that's for sure.

00:39:37.140 --> 00:39:38.440
I have to make hard
decisions about priorities

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:39.740
that I didn't have to do before.

00:39:39.740 --> 00:39:44.050
So when I first started,
you know, I was writing

00:39:44.050 --> 00:39:48.110
in the morning between
five and seven.

00:39:48.110 --> 00:39:51.640
No one had ever heard of me,
no one knew anything about it,

00:39:51.640 --> 00:39:53.870
no one was waiting
for the Philippe book

00:39:53.870 --> 00:39:55.530
or the Galloglass book.

00:39:55.530 --> 00:40:03.260
And I was just writing in the
morning, and then I would go off

00:40:03.260 --> 00:40:06.940
and teach my classes and then
I'd cook dinner and, you know,

00:40:06.940 --> 00:40:14.290
pet the dogs and go to sleep
and start the next day.

00:40:14.290 --> 00:40:18.400
But now I have a couple of --

00:40:18.400 --> 00:40:23.020
you know, in addition to being
a writer and a professor,

00:40:23.020 --> 00:40:28.060
I'm an author, which is this
part of my life is coming

00:40:28.060 --> 00:40:29.820
and meeting you, which I love.

00:40:29.820 --> 00:40:34.670
And I'm also, of course,
working on the TV show

00:40:34.670 --> 00:40:37.640
as an executive producer.

00:40:37.640 --> 00:40:40.140
So that's a lot of
different hats to wear.

00:40:40.140 --> 00:40:44.680
And sometimes I have
to make decisions

00:40:44.680 --> 00:40:51.370
about doing one thing
instead of the other

00:40:51.370 --> 00:40:53.280
or pushing something aside.

00:40:53.280 --> 00:40:58.160
And that is honestly
the hardest part

00:40:58.160 --> 00:41:01.790
of my new life is juggling --

00:41:01.790 --> 00:41:05.980
but listen, I'm talking to a
whole room of multitaskers.

00:41:05.980 --> 00:41:08.330
We're all juggling.

00:41:08.330 --> 00:41:13.580
It's just that those are my
particular balls in the air.

00:41:13.580 --> 00:41:16.530
So that's my challenge
at the moment.

00:41:16.530 --> 00:41:17.830
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:41:17.830 --> 00:41:19.130
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness:
I'm a work in progress.

00:41:19.130 --> 00:41:20.430
Hey.

00:41:20.430 --> 00:41:21.730
&gt;&gt; Hi.

00:41:21.730 --> 00:41:23.030
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Hi.

00:41:23.030 --> 00:41:24.330
&gt;&gt; You referenced sharing
experiences and wanting

00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:25.630
to know experiences
with reading,

00:41:25.630 --> 00:41:27.910
and you shared a positive one.

00:41:27.910 --> 00:41:32.380
Could you share your first or
strongest negative experience

00:41:32.380 --> 00:41:34.440
with a book and how that shaped
you as a person and an author?

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:35.740
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Yes.

00:41:35.740 --> 00:41:37.040
I just got chills.

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:38.340
I can tell you when it happened.

00:41:38.340 --> 00:41:39.640
It was last spring.

00:41:39.640 --> 00:41:41.230
I was teaching the
history of the book,

00:41:41.230 --> 00:41:43.380
and one of my students
decided that they wanted

00:41:43.380 --> 00:41:45.600
to do a project on Mein Kampf.

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:48.280
And they wanted to do it
because they'd been to a museum

00:41:48.280 --> 00:41:49.580
and there was a copy
of Mein Kampf in a --

00:41:49.580 --> 00:41:50.920
kind of in a corner in a
museum, a Holocaust Museum.

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:52.330
And they thought that it should
have a more prominent place

00:41:52.330 --> 00:41:53.740
in the museum because it
had been so instrumental.

00:41:53.740 --> 00:41:55.040
And I said to her,
well, have you looked

00:41:55.040 --> 00:41:56.340
and seen how many copies of
Mein Kampf we have here at USC?

00:41:56.340 --> 00:41:57.640
So we did, and we discovered

00:41:57.640 --> 00:41:58.940
that we had almost two dozen
copies of Mein Kampf at SC.

00:41:58.940 --> 00:42:00.280
And I had to put in a request
for Mein Kampf to call them

00:42:00.280 --> 00:42:01.580
up out of the stacks
in rare books.

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:02.880
And when I went to pick up
Mein Kampf, I felt like --

00:42:02.880 --> 00:42:04.180
first of all, I didn't want
to walk across the library

00:42:04.180 --> 00:42:05.480
with this copy of
this book in my hand

00:42:05.480 --> 00:42:06.780
because it had a certain
kind of power for me

00:42:06.780 --> 00:42:08.080
that was very negative.

00:42:08.080 --> 00:42:09.380
And I also felt like
I had to explain

00:42:09.380 --> 00:42:10.680
to the librarian
why I was taking it

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:11.980
out because I didn't want
them to think I wanted

00:42:11.980 --> 00:42:13.280
to read Mein Kampf because
I liked what it said.

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:14.580
And it gave me an insight
into all of the people

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:15.880
who were afraid to have a
book in their possession

00:42:15.880 --> 00:42:17.180
because the power that
book had in public.

00:42:17.180 --> 00:42:18.480
I had never -- I could
not understand that.

00:42:18.480 --> 00:42:19.780
I could not understand why
somebody would think having a

00:42:19.780 --> 00:42:21.080
copy of Copernicus's
work on the revolution

00:42:21.080 --> 00:42:22.380
of the spheres would
be dangerous.

00:42:22.380 --> 00:42:23.680
And I didn't feel that
until I actually had to go

00:42:23.680 --> 00:42:24.980
to my own university library and
ask them to go into rare books

00:42:24.980 --> 00:42:26.280
and pull out a copy
of Mein Kampf for me.

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:27.580
So that was my first really
chilling experience with a book

00:42:27.580 --> 00:42:28.880
of power in a negative way.

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:30.180
