00:42:56.180 --> 00:42:57.480
&gt;&gt; Going off the negative books,

00:42:57.480 --> 00:42:58.780
I just was wondering what do
you think about Isaac Newton

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:00.080
or if you could speak
about him using, like --

00:43:00.080 --> 00:43:01.380
Isaac Newton, and how he would
go to London to travel to get --

00:43:01.380 --> 00:43:02.680
what you call it -- censored
books, and he did it in secret,

00:43:02.680 --> 00:43:03.980
if you could talk a
little bit about that.

00:43:03.980 --> 00:43:05.280
&gt;&gt; Deborah Harkness: Yeah.

00:43:05.280 --> 00:43:06.580
Isaac Newton was a great
reader of banned books.

00:43:06.580 --> 00:43:07.880
He was also a terrible
defacer of books.

00:43:07.880 --> 00:43:09.180
One of the things that
Newton used to do was

00:43:09.180 --> 00:43:10.480
to take the corner of books'
pages and he'd bend them

00:43:10.480 --> 00:43:13.550
so that the point pointed
to the passage in the book

00:43:13.550 --> 00:43:15.800
that he wanted to read.

00:43:15.800 --> 00:43:19.470
So you can go through Newton's
old books, and all you have --

00:43:19.470 --> 00:43:22.550
they will actually let
you bend the corner down.

00:43:22.550 --> 00:43:24.100
There's, like, a crease.

00:43:24.100 --> 00:43:26.710
And you can do that and
then see what it was

00:43:26.710 --> 00:43:28.090
that he wanted to remember.

00:43:28.090 --> 00:43:29.390
Don't do this with
library books, right?

00:43:29.390 --> 00:43:31.130
[ Laughter ]

00:43:31.130 --> 00:43:32.840
But that was what Newton did.

00:43:32.840 --> 00:43:35.370
So he was somebody
who was always

00:43:35.370 --> 00:43:37.060
into secret forms of knowledge.

00:43:37.060 --> 00:43:39.820
You know, one of the most
humbling things in my life was

00:43:39.820 --> 00:43:43.950
to realize that sort of Newton
had devised calculus in 18 days.

00:43:43.950 --> 00:43:49.220
But he had spent decades on a
single alchemical experiment.

00:43:49.220 --> 00:43:50.870
So what we remember Newton

00:43:50.870 --> 00:43:53.740
for is not necessarily what
Newton was spending most

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:58.060
of his time doing, and
that includes his reading.

00:43:58.060 --> 00:43:59.360
Because you would think

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:01.260
that what he would be doing
was reading everybody else's

00:44:01.260 --> 00:44:02.810
scientific works.

00:44:02.810 --> 00:44:04.890
He wasn't.

00:44:04.890 --> 00:44:07.090
He was reading other
stuff and then coming

00:44:07.090 --> 00:44:09.490
up with scientific
ideas of his own.

00:44:09.490 --> 00:44:10.920
He wasn't all that interested

00:44:10.920 --> 00:44:12.700
in what his fellow
scientists were doing,

00:44:12.700 --> 00:44:15.860
which is why somebody like
Edmond Halley had to go and say,

00:44:15.860 --> 00:44:18.320
you know, could we
please have the principia

00:44:18.320 --> 00:44:19.630
out of your desk drawer?

00:44:19.630 --> 00:44:21.150
Because some of us
would like to read it.

00:44:21.150 --> 00:44:24.340
So he was a -- he had a very
interesting relationship

00:44:24.340 --> 00:44:25.640
with his books.

00:44:25.640 --> 00:44:28.620
He also used to write in
the margins of his books

00:44:28.620 --> 00:44:31.680
and between the lines
of his books.

00:44:31.680 --> 00:44:34.180
And when he ran out of room,
he'd turn the book around,

00:44:34.180 --> 00:44:36.600
and he'd go the other way.

00:44:36.600 --> 00:44:38.840
So he was a crafty
old guy, that Newton.

00:44:38.840 --> 00:44:42.480
So if any of you are, you
know, personal book defacers,

00:44:42.480 --> 00:44:44.160
you come from a long tradition

00:44:44.160 --> 00:44:45.460
of great minds like
Isaac Newton.

00:44:45.460 --> 00:44:46.760
[ Laughter ]

00:44:46.760 --> 00:44:48.060
Anyway, great questions.

00:44:48.060 --> 00:44:49.360
Wonderful to meet you all.

00:44:49.360 --> 00:44:50.660
I hope I see you in
